  "why": "The method enforces input plausibility by design. Instead of applying mutations to existing audio files, which risks cumulative distortion and degradation of semantic validity, the paper's method generates new audio inputs from a text corpus using a Text-to-Speech (TTS) system. A TTS system is a generative model trained to produce realistic and semantically valid speech, which inherently restricts the generated inputs to a plausible distribution. To further ensure plausibility and handle cases where the TTS system might produce invalid audio, the method employs a filtering mechanism based on differential testing. An audio input is only considered a 'valid test case' if at least one of a panel of cross-referenced ASR systems can successfully transcribe it. This process effectively discards generated audios that are too distorted or syntactically invalid to be recognized, ensuring that the inputs used for testing remain within the domain of plausible human speech.",
